                    },
                    "message": "Would 'eventHandler' be more clear for the name?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "power-control-x86/src/power_control.cpp",
                    "line": 1065,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Sure -- especially in the context of the other change eliminating the \"intermediate\" handler."
                },
                {
                    "file": "power-control-x86/src/power_control.cpp",
                    "line": 1081,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "From what I've read I *think* this should be OK, but I'm far from a C++ expert, so if someone with deeper knowledge of the language than I could confirm that this isn't going to do something silly like leak a closure on every invocation or something, that would be appreciated."
                },
                {
                    "file": "power-control-x86/src/power_control.cpp",
                    "line": 1081,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jason Bills",
                        "email": "jason.m.bills@linux.intel.com",
                        "username": "jmbills"
                    },
                    "message": "This works on my system, but there is a more common implementation for these kinds of loops that is very close to this.  Basically, just move the async_wait() call into a function and re-call the function from the handler:\n\nstatic void waitForGPIOEvent(const std::string& name,\n                             const std::function<void(bool)>& innerHandler,\n                             gpiod::line& line,\n                             boost::asio::posix::stream_descriptor& event)\n{\n    event.async_wait(\n        boost::asio::posix::stream_descriptor::wait_read,\n        [&name, innerHandler, &line,\n         &event](const boost::system::error_code ec) {\n            if (ec)\n            {\n                std::string errMsg =\n                    name + \" fd handler error: \" + ec.message();\n                phosphor::logging::log<phosphor::logging::level::ERR>(\n                    errMsg.c_str());\n                // TODO: throw here to force power-control to restart?\n                return;\n            }\n            gpiod::line_event line_event = line.event_read();\n            innerHandler(line_event.event_type ==\n                         gpiod::line_event::RISING_EDGE);\n            waitForGPIOEvent(name, innerHandler, line, event);\n        });\n}\n\nI tested with calling waitForGPIOEvent() instead of async_wait() on line 1123 below and it also works on my system."
                },
                {
                    "file": "power-control-x86/src/power_control.cpp",
                    "line": 1081,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Ah -- yeah, that does look like a cleaner arrangement, thanks."
                }
            ],
